<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="268" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1558,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1594,1619]" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Etymology.</emphasis>
We dedicated this new genus to Dr. María Marta Cigliano, as an acknowledgement to her scientific work and her continued and interesting contributions to the knowledge of the subfamily Melanoplinae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="271" pageId="1" pageNumber="268" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1558,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1666,1691]" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Slender insects, matte and slightly coarse body surface (particularly the pronotum) (
<figureCitation box="[1279,1388,1666,1691]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[171,1434,478,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[171,1434,478,1967]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 2. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). Habitus lateral and dorsal respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828467/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,206,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,205,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 18. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (in live condition). 17. Male. 18. Female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828473/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">17, 18</figureCitation>
). Frons slightly convex in both sexes, eyes prominent but not noticeably surpassing the vertex level (
<figureCitation box="[1350,1431,1702,1727]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,195,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1903]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 11. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). 3. Frons. 4. Tegmina. 5 – 6. Terminalia in lateral and dorsal view. 7 – 11. Genitalia: 7. Epiphallus. 8 – 9. Genitalia without epiphallus in lateral and dorsal view. 10 – 11. Details of aedeagus in lateral and dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,182,1739,1763]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[163,1429,193,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[163,1429,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 16. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Female). 12 – 13. Head, pronotum and tegmina in lateral and dorsal view. 14 – 16. Terminalia in dorsal, lateral and ventral view respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828471/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">12</figureCitation>
). Metazona a little longer than the prozona, males with the hind margin of pronotum rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1258,1327,1738,1763]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[171,1434,478,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[171,1434,478,1967]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 2. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). Habitus lateral and dorsal respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828467/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), females with hind margin of pronotum straight (
<figureCitation box="[597,679,1774,1799]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[163,1429,193,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[163,1429,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 16. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Female). 12 – 13. Head, pronotum and tegmina in lateral and dorsal view. 14 – 16. Terminalia in dorsal, lateral and ventral view respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828471/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
); pronotum mid-line present along all the pronotal disc. Both sexes brachypterous (
<figureCitation box="[327,468,1810,1835]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,206,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,205,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 18. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (in live condition). 17. Male. 18. Female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828473/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Figs. 17, 18</figureCitation>
). Male: Cerci slender, upwardly curving from mesal portion to tip, reduced furculae (
<figureCitation box="[159,230,1846,1871]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,195,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1903]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 11. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). 3. Frons. 4. Tegmina. 5 – 6. Terminalia in lateral and dorsal view. 7 – 11. Genitalia: 7. Epiphallus. 8 – 9. Genitalia without epiphallus in lateral and dorsal view. 10 – 11. Details of aedeagus in lateral and dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Phallic complex: Cingulum with the endophallic plates expanding (
<figureCitation box="[1026,1095,1846,1871]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,195,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1903]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 11. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). 3. Frons. 4. Tegmina. 5 – 6. Terminalia in lateral and dorsal view. 7 – 11. Genitalia: 7. Epiphallus. 8 – 9. Genitalia without epiphallus in lateral and dorsal view. 10 – 11. Details of aedeagus in lateral and dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), valves of the aedeagus slim and distally divergent (
<figureCitation box="[409,491,1882,1907]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,195,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1903]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 11. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). 3. Frons. 4. Tegmina. 5 – 6. Terminalia in lateral and dorsal view. 7 – 11. Genitalia: 7. Epiphallus. 8 – 9. Genitalia without epiphallus in lateral and dorsal view. 10 – 11. Details of aedeagus in lateral and dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
), slightly sclerotized distally, sheath of aedeagus dorsally covering the valves of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[270,356,1918,1943]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,195,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1903]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 11. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (Male). 3. Frons. 4. Tegmina. 5 – 6. Terminalia in lateral and dorsal view. 7 – 11. Genitalia: 7. Epiphallus. 8 – 9. Genitalia without epiphallus in lateral and dorsal view. 10 – 11. Details of aedeagus in lateral and dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Body color mostly brownish-gray with olive green extremities (
<figureCitation box="[1105,1190,1918,1943]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,206,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,205,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 18. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (in live condition). 17. Male. 18. Female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828473/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
); in females, chevron femora filled with black (
<figureCitation box="[443,528,1954,1979]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1962,1984]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,206,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,205,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 18. Ciglianacris submontana n. sp. (in live condition). 17. Male. 18. Female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828473/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="268">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
); post-ocular stripe present, extending along the lateral margin of the pronotum until the fourth abdominal tergite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,368,151,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Relationships.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[376,516,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae" genus="Ciglianacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[376,516,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Ciglianacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[524,602,151,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[524,597,151,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">n. gen</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, closely resembles the other Andean genera 
<taxonomicName box="[1112,1235,153,176]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Bogotacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1112,1235,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Bogotacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1292,1429,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Chibchacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1292,1429,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Chibchacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs by not having a completely shiny-smooth body surface. The head of the aforementioned two genera tends to be noticeably more slanted and shiny, with a more pronounced fastigium. This new genus seems to be closer to 
<taxonomicName box="[289,412,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Bogotacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[289,412,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Bogotacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to 
<taxonomicName box="[506,643,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Chibchacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[506,643,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Chibchacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as it does not have modified tips of the cerci (a common character in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,288,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Chibchacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,288,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Chibchacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Also, the aedeagus valves of 
<taxonomicName box="[634,774,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae" genus="Ciglianacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[634,774,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">Ciglianacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are thin and not very sclerotized, and they are enveloped in a membrane-like fold (or sheath of aedeagus), in contrast with the other two genera, where they are well sclerotized and not covered in any fold whatsoever, or if the sheath of aedeagus is present in these genera not is so developed as the new genus.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1131,1990,2013]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828467/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="269" targetBox="[171,1434,478,1941]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1131,1990,2013]" box="[151,1131,1990,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,731,1990,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="269">
